  "node-operator-binding.v1 (subject-to-node evidence for predicate evaluation)"
  "node-address-attestation.v1 (P043 attestation evidence)"
  "Solution 028 temporal storage convention (event log + projection + replay)"
  "Solution 057 notifications (operator notifications for migration and class events)"]

 :produces
 ["relationship-class.v1 (current class definition projection)"
  "relationship-class-changed.v1 (append-only class transition facts)"
  "relationship-membership-fact.v1 (append-only membership facts)"
  "pairwise-nym-binding-fact.v1 (append-only nym continuity facts)"
  "pairwise-nym-binding.v1 (sealed projection of latest nym binding state)"
  "relationship-policy-predicate.v1 (declarative trust requirement)"
  "relationship-policy-candidate.v1 (host-internal eligibility input)"
  "relationship-policy-decision.v1 (host-bound autonomous decision)"
  "contacts.membership-changed.v1 (legacy projection during Phase 2)"]

 :notes
 ["This is the first Pseudonym Vault-backed application of relationship state. Messaging, Artifact Delivery, and Contact Catalog cease to own partial models."
  "The three-tier predicate/candidate/decision split matches the `label != authority` invariant. Candidate means 'may be basis'; decision means 'host bound a specific bounded effect'; real authority still flows through capability/passport/admission."
  "Default class seeds for `contacts` and `friends` are operator-editable defaults, not magic constants. They are written via the same `relationship-class-changed.v1` event as any operator-driven change, so audit is uniform."
  "The middleware boundary (no direct read of sealed state) is the single biggest implementation invariant. Any future capability that would let middleware see membership directly must be rejected at design review."
  "Phase 1 and Phase 2 are committed in the first iteration. Phase 3 (writes fully migrated) and Phase 4 (legacy deprecation) are deferred."
  "No new public protocol capability in this iteration. Local Relationship Layer is exposed only through local-authenticated host capabilities consumed by in-process and supervised middleware. A future public capability for federated consumers is explicitly deferred."]}
